Got this app while it was on sale for free, and for its intended purpose of being a time passer that should be played in a patient manner, Hook fulfills this role rather well. Consists of 50 levels that become progressively more complex where you restart the level if you make a mistake, with a life system included for the later levels to allow for multiple mistakes before a reset, and replayability in the form of scrolling between the levels beaten. A short, relaxing game overall.

Originally, a Kongregate game, Hook is a minimalistic puzzler that made its way to mobile, Steam etc. due to the massive response it received on Kongregate. I came to Hook after having played Targaciej's other minimalistic puzzler, Klocki. Sign of a great minimalistic puzzler is that the mechanics should be intuitive enough for the player to figure out by simply engaging with the game - something this game excels at. With no information provided, you are thrown into the first level, which incidentally happens to be the title screen. And one by one you figure out the challenges the game has to provide while listening to the soothing music playing in the background. The difficulty level of puzzles in Hook is a little lower compared to the puzzles in Klocki but certainly not low enough to make solving the puzzles a trivial task. After completing the two Rainbow Train games I have come to conclusion that Targaciej has mastered the art of making minimaliatic games. Consider me a fan, Mr. Targaciej. I look forward to playing oO and any future releases you might have lined up. :)

I played for awhile, then the next thing I knew I was at the last level (50) and Game Over. I was expecting a larger degree of difficulty when hit 50, but instead, I received a "Game Over" screen, just when I was getting into it.  So just an FYI if you are looking at this game, it is worth a buck for an hour of taking your brain off whatever you are currently working on, since it does take some concentration on the higher levels.  I only wish it a was a bit more challenging at the higher levels.  Technical note:  On the Moto-X size screen there is too little of a gap on the line breaks, which makes it difficult to determine which is the next line to eliminate.  I haven't tried it on a larger phone or tablet, but I expect it would be easier to distinguish the breaks.
